						               													<description>&amp;quot;Toward ten o'clock I could sense an added nervousness. Commanders asked more often&amp;#10;Whether there were any changes.&amp;quot; &amp;ndash;Yael Dayan&amp;rsquo;s comments following a command meeting by Sharon and his officers early in the attack at Abu Ageila, June 5, 1967.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Hot Sand, Cold Steel is an introductory-level wargame simulation of the battle of Abu Ageila, fought in the Sinai between the Egyptian 2nd Infantry Division and elements of General Ariel Sharon&amp;rsquo;s armored Ugdah (division).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players are cast in the roles of the local commanders on this battlefield.  Both will be challenged to do as well, or better than their historical counterparts.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each copy of Hot Sand, Cold Steel includes the following:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    Eighty single-sided, unmounted counters&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    Two 11 by 17 inch hex map sheets&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    One Players&amp;rsquo; Aid Sheet&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    8 pages of rules&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players will also need one six-sided die to play the game. Each hex is about three quarters of a kilometer across.  A turn represents two hours of time.  Each unit is either a battalion (II) or company (I).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Hot Sand, Cold Steel is designed by Paul Rohrbaugh and features graphics by Tim Allen.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
